 seem insoluble: carbon emissions, overshoot, inequality, joblessness, and a dysfunctional food system. Can we change direction, move away from business as usual, and achieve a more sustainable, empowering, and humane economy? Through a fascinating array of illuminating case studies, this hope-filled book affirms that we can. In locations across the United States and around the globe, local participants are forging their own versions of small-scale, low-footprint, high-satisfaction lifestyles and communities. From raw-milk consumers and members of alternative agricultural initiatives to time bankers, artisan producers in the Aude region of France, and bicycle mechanics on the South Side of Chicago, individuals and small groups are exploring the practice of plenitude. Their efforts demonstrate how social and economic transformation happens and suggest new paths toward larger-scale change and a richer quality of life for all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSustainable development. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aCarfagna, Lindsey B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubois, Emilie A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGowan, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolt, Douglas B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHébert, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMincyte, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPress, Melea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchor, Juliet B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchor, Juliet B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSlocum, Rachel, econtributo